<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,758]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52">
Remarks: This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[630,765,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Drabescus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gressitti">
<emphasis box="[630,765,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="52">D. gressitti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in external appearance but differs from the latter in: 
<number box="[1411,1424,577,603]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52" value="1.0">1</number>
) forewing with pale transverse band across wing at apex of clavus; 
<number box="[938,953,616,642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
) pygofer broad at base and narrowing to apex, with long process posteriorly; 
<number box="[594,609,654,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52" value="3.0">3</number>
) connective with apical margin dorsally incurved; 
<number box="[1230,1246,654,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
) aedeagus with shaft bifurcate at apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,152,758]" box="[197,1047,732,758]" pageId="3" pageNumber="52">Etymology: This species is named for its bifurcate apex of the aedeagus.</paragraph>
